Comment: This is a game  of 91 moves that was played in 1851. White opened with e2-e4.
Black e7-e5
White brings out Nb1-c3.
Black Ng8-f6.
White puts out a pawn 2 spaces to f4 opening a view for the queen.
Black moves up a pawn 2 spaces in the center to d5 attacking pawn on e4. This move allows the LSB and the DSB room to develope. This is a great move.
White pawn captures the first pawn in the game and now is on d5 with back up of the knight on c3.
Black advances pawn further to e4.
White moves pawn up 2 spaces from d2-d4 and avoids any contact with pawn on e4.
Black bishop moves to b4 and pins the knight on c3.
White develops a bishop from f1-c4.
Black moves knight to d5.
White takes knight Bc4xd5.
Black queen now takes advantage of the pinned knight and Qd8xd5 taking the LSB.
White brings out Ng1-e2 protecting 2 pawns on d4 and f4. This move is setting up a king side castle that will also protect the rook on h1 if Black were to keep advancing pawn on the e-file.
Black now sends out LSB from c8-g4 attacking knight on e2.
White castles O-O.  Does this seem to be the only move white should of taken? White had 2 pinned knights before the castling and now has only knight on e2 pinned.
Black Bb4xc3 takes whites knight.
White moves the pinned knight and takes the bishop  Ne2xc3.  And is able to attack  Blacks queen on d5.
Black moves queen from the attacking knight  Qd5-d7
